The paper deals with signal processing and information theory, specifically the computation of the Walsh-Hadamard transform (WHT) of a signal with sub-linear sparsity in the transform domain. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.SP (Signal Processing) are the most likely categories. The paper also uses tools from coding theory, which suggests cs.CC (Computational Complexity) as another possible category. The algorithm presented in the paper involves subsampling and belief propagation, which are techniques commonly used in distributed systems and networks, making cs.DS (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) a likely category as well. Finally, the paper discusses the performance of the algorithm in different sparsity regimes, which could fall under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
